result:
Here are the confirmed correctness bugs:

---

**`src/core/api/providers/bedrock.ts` — `executeConverseStream`** (line 744)

```ts
const thinkingContent = delta.thinking || delta.text || ""
```
`delta.text` is regular text content (from `text_delta` chunks). The `|| delta.text` fallback means if `delta.thinking` is absent or empty, regular text gets emitted as reasoning. It should be `delta.thinking || ""`.

---

**`src/core/api/providers/mistral.ts` — stream response loop** (lines 109–118)

```ts
yield {
    type: "tool_calls",
    tool_call: {
        function: { id: toolCall.id, name: ..., arguments: ... },
        // missing call_id
    },
}
```
Every other provider (confirmed by `gemini.test.ts:138` and `StreamResponseHandler.ts:247`) sets `call_id` at the `tool_call` top level. Without it, `StreamResponseHandler.processToolUseDelta` can't correlate tool results back to their calls — it falls back to a random `nanoid(8)` rather than the actual call ID, breaking tool-result matching.

Two confirmed correctness bugs:

---

**`src/core/api/providers/xai.ts` — `createMessage()`**

Variable shadowing at lines 50–56. `let reasoningEffort` is declared in the outer scope (line 50), then re-declared with `let` inside the `if` block (line 52), creating a new block-scoped variable. All assignments inside the block affect the inner variable; the outer one stays `undefined`. So `reasoning_effort: reasoningEffort` at line 64 is always `undefined`, even for grok-3-mini models.

```ts
let reasoningEffort: ... | undefined        // outer — never written
if (modelId.includes("3-mini")) {
    let reasoningEffort = this.options...   // inner shadows outer
    if (...) reasoningEffort = undefined    // modifies inner only
}
// reasoning_effort: reasoningEffort → always undefined
```

Fix: remove the inner `let` so the assignment targets the outer variable.

---

**`src/core/api/providers/mistral.ts` — `createMessage()`**

Tool call yielded with wrong shape (lines 109–118). The `id` is placed inside `function` instead of as `call_id` at the top level:

```ts
yield {
    type: "tool_calls",
    tool_call: {
        function: {
            id: toolCall.id,   // ← wrong: should be call_id at top level
            name: ...,
            arguments: ...,
        },
    },
}
```

`src/shared/messages/content.ts:18` defines `call_id` at the `tool_call` level, and `ToolResultUtils.ts` reads `block.call_id` (not `block.function.id`). This means Mistral tool calls will never match their results — `call_id` will be `undefined`, falling back to `"cline"` for all calls.
